    <item>
      <title>Markdown Features Demo</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/articles/markdown-features-demo/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/articles/markdown-features-demo/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;This article demonstrates all the markdown and shortcode features available in the Flavor theme.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;text-formatting&#34;&gt;Text Formatting&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Standard markdown formatting works as expected:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Bold text&lt;/strong&gt; with &lt;code&gt;**bold**&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Italic text&lt;/em&gt; with &lt;code&gt;*italic*&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;del&gt;Strikethrough&lt;/del&gt; with &lt;code&gt;~~strikethrough~~&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;Inline code&lt;/code&gt; with backticks&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://example.com&#34;&gt;Links&lt;/a&gt; with &lt;code&gt;[text](url)&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;wikilinks&#34;&gt;Wikilinks&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Link to other notes using double brackets:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;[[The Atomic Notes Principle]] - Link by title&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;[[atomic notes|Atomic Notes]] - Custom display text&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;[[Note-Taking]] - Link to MOC pages&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Or use the shortcode directly: &lt;a href=&#34;http://localhost:1313/notes/evergreen-notes/&#34; class=&#34;wikilink text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline&#34; data-wikilink-target=&#34;/notes/evergreen-notes/&#34;&gt;Evergreen Notes&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Building a Knowledge Graph</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/articles/building-a-knowledge-graph/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 03 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/articles/building-a-knowledge-graph/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The knowledge graph visualizes connections between notes. It turns the abstract idea of &amp;ldquo;linked thinking&amp;rdquo; into something you can see and explore.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;why-visualize&#34;&gt;Why Visualize?&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Our brains are visual. A list of backlinks tells you &lt;em&gt;what&lt;/em&gt; connects, but a graph shows you &lt;em&gt;how&lt;/em&gt; the connections form patterns.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;figure class=&#34;admonition not-prose rounded-lg p-4 mb-4 border-l-4 bg-blue-50 border-blue-500 dark:bg-blue-900/20 dark:border-blue-400&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;figcaption class=&#34;flex items-center gap-2 font-semibold mb-2 text-gray-900 dark:text-white&#34;&gt;&lt;svg xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/2000/svg&#34; width=&#34;24&#34; height=&#34;24&#34; viewBox=&#34;0 0 24 24&#34; fill=&#34;none&#34; stroke=&#34;currentColor&#34; stroke-width=&#34;2&#34; stroke-linecap=&#34;round&#34; stroke-linejoin=&#34;round&#34; class=&#34;w-5 h-5 text-blue-500&#34;&gt;&lt;circle cx=&#34;12&#34; cy=&#34;12&#34; r=&#34;10&#34;/&gt;&lt;path d=&#34;M12 16v-4&#34;/&gt;&lt;path d=&#34;M12 8h.01&#34;/&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&#xA;&lt;span&gt;Try It&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/figcaption&gt;&#xA;  &lt;div class=&#34;prose dark:prose-invert prose-sm max-w-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;    Open the &lt;a href=&#34;http://localhost:1313/graph/&#34;&gt;full-page graph&lt;/a&gt; to explore. Drag nodes, filter by section, toggle link types.&#xA;  &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;how-it-works&#34;&gt;How It Works&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The graph uses D3.js force simulation. Each note becomes a node; each link becomes an edge.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Getting Started with Zettelkasten</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/articles/getting-started-with-zettelkasten/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 01 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/articles/getting-started-with-zettelkasten/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The Zettelkasten (&amp;ldquo;slip box&amp;rdquo; in German) is a note-taking method that transforms how you think and write. Developed by sociologist Niklas Luhmann, who used it to write over 70 books, the system creates a network of interconnected ideas.&lt;span class=&#34;sidenote-mark text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400&#34; aria-details=&#34;sidenote-content-01&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;sup class=&#34;font-semibold&#34;&gt;01&lt;/sup&gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&lt;small id=&#34;sidenote-content-01&#34; class=&#34;sidenote text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 xl:float-left xl:clear-left xl:w-48 xl:ml-[-13rem] xl:mt-0 mt-2 mb-2 block xl:block bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 p-2 rounded xl:bg-transparent xl:dark:bg-transparent xl:p-0&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;span class=&#34;sr-only&#34;&gt;(sidenote: &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;  &lt;sup class=&#34;font-semibold text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 xl:inline hidden&#34;&gt;01&lt;/sup&gt;&#xA;  Luhmann maintained his Zettelkasten on paper index cards. Modern digital tools make the method even more powerful.&#xA;  &lt;span class=&#34;sr-only&#34;&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&lt;/small&gt;&#xA;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
